<HL>
   Tuesday's Markets:
   Stock Prices Rise
   On Successful Sale
   Of 3-Year Notes
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   The successful sale of $10.5 billion in three-year
Treasury notes touched off a last-minute rally that helped
stock prices rack up a seventh consecutive gain.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 11.94 to 2733.56 in
light trading. The gains came in a last-minute flurry of
activity after news that the Treasury auction went better
than some analysts had expected. The dollar was mixed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Nervousness about the auction kept stock prices confined
to a narrow range in sluggish trading through much of the
day. But investors had been encouraged by one sign that
interest rates may have peaked: steadily declining estimates
over the past week of the yield that would attract investors
to the Treasury's $30.5 billion of notes and bonds during the
three-day auction. The average yield on the $10.5 billion of
three-year notes sold yesterday was 8.74%, at the low end of
most estimates.
   Despite the relative success of yesterday's auction, stock
investors remain wary about the outcome of the remaining
sales. The Treasury will auction $10 billion in 10-year notes
today and $10 billion of 30-year bonds tomorrow. The bond
sale has the most potential to disrupt financial markets as
it is regarded as the best barometer of inflation
expectations.
</TEXT>
