WSJ900509-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900509-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Landmark Land's
   $967 Million Deal
   Runs Into Hurdle
   ----
   By Neil Barsky
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   LML
</CO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   When Landmark Land Co. announced plans last month to sell
a substantial portion of its real estate for $967 million, it
seemed to some real-estate analysts that the deal was too
good to be true. They may have been right.
   Carmel, Calif.-based Landmark said the Office of Thrift
Supervision objected to the financing for the sale of its
resort and real-estate properties to California developer
Barry G. Hon. Landmark said it would try to propose a new
deal, which could include Mr. Hon acquiring new partners or
additional lenders.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Real-estate analysts were skeptical the deal could be put
together again at the same price, however.
   "Landmark was trying to show a real big gain by boosting
its capital position," said Bert Ely, an Alexandria,
Va.-based financial institutions consultant. "Now, if they
have to go to a third party to sell, they won't be able to
show nearly the gain."
   The sticking point for the OTS was that the sale, 75% of
which was to be financed by Landmark's Oak Tree Savings unit,
would have committed about 20% of Oak Tree's assets to one
borrower. It wasn't clear how Mr. Hon, a Southern California
developer, would finance what remained of the acquisition.
   The Landmark sale was triggered by the Financial
Institutions Reform, Recovery and Enforcement Act of 1989,
which increased the amount of capital that savings and loan
associations needed to stay in the real-estate business. As a
result of the act, a number of S&amp;Ls have sold their real
estate at deflated prices.
   Landmark's real-estate holdings are owned through Oak
Tree, which is based in New Orleans. In April, Landmark said
it would realize a pretax profit of $470 million if the
entire transaction were completed.
   Landmark, a thinly traded land and golf-course development
company, is 28%-owned by Gerald G. Barton and 24% owned by
Toronto-based Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd., which is
controlled by the Reichmann brothers.
   Landmark officials say they believe the deal will be
salvaged. "There are several things Mr. Hon can do," said Mr.
Barton, Landmark's chairman. "He can find partners, raise
more equity or have one of his own banks finance part of it.
I feel pretty confident he will do one of those things."
   Bruce Tester, an attorney for Mr. Hon, said Landmark would
soon discuss the matter with OTS officials and try to
reconfigure the sale.
   While Mr. Barton said he was surprised by the OTS finding,
Wall Street apparently was already skeptical that the deal
would be completed. The day the proposed transaction with Mr.
Hon was announced, the stock opened at $17.50 a share, and
has fallen steadily ever since. In American Stock Exchange
Trading yesterday, Landmark stock dropped $1.875 to $10.375.
   "The stock price is telling us this deal has long odds of
happening," said Kenneth Campbell, president of Audit
Investments Inc., a Montvale, N.J., advisory concern that
follows real-estate companies. "In today's real-estate
market, it was always a very speculative deal."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900509-0118
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900509-0118.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Pickens Violates Japan's Keiretsu
</HL>
<DATE>
05/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   T. Boone Pickens faces real difficulties in attempting to
deal with the Japanese, but his comments on the "keiretsu"
system ("Secrets Koito Hoped to Hide by Keeping Me Off Its
Board," editorial page, March 28) are off the mark.
   Doing business in Japan is no piece of cake. Embedded in
the intricacies of Japanese culture, keiretsu present
formidable hurdles. The links among distributors, in
particular, are so involved and inefficient as to defy
ordinary logic. But keiretsu are not, as Mr. Pickens
grandiosely asserts, "the root of the world's trade problems
with Japan," including his own snafu with Koito Manufacturing
Co.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The keiretsu is a system of lifetime business
relationships built more on trust than on signed contracts.
To break such a relationship just because someone else --
Japanese or foreign -- offers a cheaper product or service is
for the Japanese a violation of trust and the worst kind of
dirty dealing.
   Keeping Mr. Pickens off the Koito board therefore is not,
as he claims, a question of Koito hiding "secrets." Those are
all public knowledge anyway. What Mr. Pickens fails to grasp
is that his approach -- assault by press release and lawsuit
-- has fulfilled every Japanese stereotype of the gun-toting
Westerner and made him an outsider to the friendship and
trust that run through business relationships in Japan. He
has made no effort to develop a proper relationship with
Koito. So it can't trust him.
   Even Americans find it difficult to trust Mr. Pickens. Can
the Japanese be blamed for keeping him at arm's length?
   Mr. Pickens's recent actions have only fanned Koito's
mistrust. He gave the company five business days to produce
10 years of financial records, then filed a lawsuit when
Koito asked for more time. His financial relationship with a
Japanese greenmailer, Kitaro Watanabe, makes his denials of
greenmail intentions unconvincing. He blithely suggested that
Koito adopt a binding resolution banning the special
repurchase of stock, ignoring the deep-seated Japanese
suspicion of anything that smacks of legal action.
   Mr. Pickens will succeed in Japan -- as the Japanese have
succeeded here -- only to the extent that he adjusts to a
strange language, culture, and economic and legal systems.
The key issue is not the keiretsu but Mr. Pickens's refusal
even to consider modifying his approach to fit Japanese
business practices.
   Instead, Mr. Pickens, in a display of cultural arrogance,
demands that Japan abandon keiretsu. So fundamental are
keiretsu to Japan that to abandon them would be to rip up
Japanese culture and identity. Who is Mr. Pickens, or anybody
else for that matter, to exact such an outrageous demand?
   It is also hypocritical, because Mr. Pickens could be
charged with attempting to form his own keiretsu. In 1988 he
locked horns with KNEnergy, seeking election to the board and
control of KN's pipeline system to secure higher prices for
his own Mesa Co.'s gas. KN CEO J. Robert Wilson unmasked Mr.
Pickens's intentions in a March 4, 1988, letter to
shareholders, accusing him of "continuing efforts to obtain
control of KN for the benefit of Mesa." That sounds
astonishingly like Mr. Pickens's unsubstantiated charges
today that Toyota, as part of the keiretsu, pressures Koito
for favorable pricing of auto parts.
   Perhaps Mr. Pickens knows even more about cartels than the
Japanese do.
   John K. Gillespie
   Intercultural Specialist and Consultant on Japan
   Clarke Consulting Group
   Redwood City, Calif.
   ---
   Mr. Pickens mistakenly identifies Japanese corporate
cross-holdings with "old-fashioned cartels." While the
tuition at leading business schools is high, it is a bargain
compared with the "tuition" Mr. Pickens and his associates
are paying in connection with their large shareholding in
Koito. Any investor would be well-advised to learn about a
foreign culture and system of corporate governance before
investing a billion dollars in that country. It appears that
Mr. Pickens invested first, and now complains as he finally
comes to understand what he owns. Perhaps he should reread
Ben Graham.
   Jack McDonald
   IBJ Professor of Finance
   Stanford Business School
   Stanford University
   Stanford, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
