   Business Brief -- General Electric Co.:
   Judge Temporarily Blocks
   Daimler Jet-Engine Projects
</HL>
<DATE>
05/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   GE G.DAI UTX
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   General Electric Co. received an order from a federal
judge temporarily blocking a Daimler-Benz AG subsidiary from
entering a series of commercial jet-engine programs with
United Technologies Corp.
   Last month, GE filed a lawsuit asking $1.15 billion of
damages, charging the West German industrial group with
breaking an agreement it has with GE to develop high-thrust
jet engines. GE charged that proprietary data that it shares
with Daimler will find its way to GE's competitor, United
Technologies, which owns the jet-engine maker Pratt &amp;
Whitney.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In Manhattan, U.S. District Judge Robert P. Patterson Jr.
scheduled a hearing for May 22. GE has requested an order
blocking Daimler and its Motoren-und Turbinen-Union unit from
entering into agreements with GE competitors on the engines
or from disclosing any GE data on the engines until the case
can be tried.
   GE, Fairfield, Conn., also has interests in financial
services and broadcasting. United Technologies, Hartford, has
diverse industrial and defense interests.
   Lewis A. Kaplan, an attorney in New York for the Daimler
subsidiary, said the unit "believes that the GE claim is
without merit and expects to prevail."
